complication. In the multivariate analysis, urgent procedure, mitral valve 
surgery and presentation of any postoperative complication were identified as 
predictors of mortality, and female sex was identified as a risk factor for 
postoperative morbidity. Survival at one, 3 and 5 years was 91.20%, 80.73% and 
69.20%, respectively. 98.7% of the patients were in I-II NYHA functional class 
and 92.5% satisfied with overall surgery outcome when they were interviewed.
CONCLUSIONS: Despite more preoperative co-morbidity and worse functional class, 
cardiac surgery in octogenarians can be performed with an acceptable mortality. 
Our patients have a satisfactory quality of life and would undergo a cardiac 
surgery procedure again. Specific measurements in preoperative and immediate 
postoperative periods, in order to reduce higher morbidity rates, are advisable.

