84/100,000 at age 51 years. These results were similar to observed data from 
German cancer registries, German literature data and results from other 
international models. Based on our model, annual Pap screening could prevent 
98.7% of diagnosed cancer cases and 99.6% of deaths due to cervical cancer in 
women completely adherent to screening and compliant to treatment. Extending the 
screening interval from 1 year to 2, 3 or 5 years resulted in reduced screening 
effectiveness.
CONCLUSIONS: This model provides a tool for evaluating the long-term 
effectiveness of different cervical cancer screening tests and strategies.

